defaultShould the government take any further any specific actions in relation to cooling? 
defaultWe know that DECC are opposed to the idea of subsidising cooling by air conditioning: we are very much in sympathy with the idea that standard air conditioning should not be encouraged – because there are large carbon emission implications. This is because
default the standard approach to cooling – heat 
defaultexchange with h
defaultot air – is expensive in electricity [and therefore carbon emissions].  The CoP (
defaultCoefficient of Performance) of 
defaulta 
defaultroof-mounted 
defaultchiller can be as low as 1.5 on a hot day [1 kilowatt of electricity is n
defaulteeded to provide 1.5 kW of cooling].  However, some cooling is necessary, and there is a very much more effective way of achieving this – by employing ground source energy and 
defaultallowing 
defaultheat
default to escape to
default cold ground instead of forcing heat into hot air.  Th
defaulte CoP of “free cooling” (heat exchange with cold ground by means of a circulation pump) can be as high as 25. The CoP of Renewable Cooling (heat exchange with cold ground 
defaultassisted by
default a reversible heat pump) can frequently achieve a CoP of 
default8
default. 
defaultThe carbon 
defaultemission savings of using Renewable Cooling, instead of standard Air Conditioning,
default are huge
default and we believe that DECC will come to see that these should be encouraged.
defaultThere will need to be appropriate safeguards, which could be defined in terms of requirin
defaultg a high CoP before Renewable Cooling is recognised and requiring a high temperature set point so that Cooling is only used when necessary (rather than as an indulgence).
defaultDECC needs to acknowledge that a by-product of Renewable Cooling is to heat the groun
defaultd. The heat in the ground becomes a major asset when heating is required the following winter. Renewable Heating makes Renewable Cooling 
defaultmore
default efficient 
defaultand vice versa
default.
defaultDECC ha
defaults 
defaultbeen 
defaultinclined to reject 
defaultsubsidy for renewable cooling as their interpretation o
defaultf the Renewable Energy Directive
default 
default(RED)
default is that it would not count as “renewable”
default,
default although it would save significant CO2 emissions. We think that DECC, which frequently claims that the RHI is a “world first”,
default should be making the case to Brusse
defaultls, rather t
defaulthan follow
defaulting
