default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe RHI provides an annual subsidy to reduce the annual cost of using renewable heat. The barrier to installing a ground source heat pump is not the annual running cost (which is 
defaultsmall) but the up-front capital cost (which is large).
default-
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe RHI effectively aims to subsidise inefficient technologies over efficient ones. DECC argues that inefficient technologies need more subsidy to be employed. This discriminates against the use of eff
defaulticient technologies like ground source heat pumps. This is the opposite of what DECC should be doing.
default-
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe RHI provides a subsidy to the owner of a building over many years if renewable heating is installed. The RHI provides no subsidy 
defaultat all 
defaultto the builder
default who often decides which form of heating will be used (and 
defaulttherefore
default chooses the cheapest capital cost).
